fire period.\n\n4. The arrangement appears to be more consistent with a limited humanitarian/prisoner-exchange pause tied to Victory Day ceremonies rather than a general halt in military engagement.\n\nOn a preponderance standard, the evidence weighs more heavily toward the arrangement being a limited, purpose-specific pause rather than the qualifying \"general pause in the conflict\" required by the proposition. The battlefield evidence showing continued operations is particularly probative of whether a general halt actually occurred.\n\nBased on this analysis, I will vote \"not_demonstrated.\""},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_cb0a","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_submit_council_vote","args":"{\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"The record shows a temporary, prisoner-exchange-focused arrangement with continued theater-wide military operations. The Ukrainian decree is narrowly limited to Red Square targeting, and battlefield evidence demonstrates ongoing engagement, falling short of the required general pause in military engagement.\"}"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"deepseek/deepseek-v3.1-terminus","usage":{"input":1854,"output":542,"cacheRead":59008,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":61404,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1782791485604,"responseId":"gen-1782791486-vO6YfKVhfpBiYv2gMHoS"}}
